Time Model Statistics

  • DB Time represents total time in user calls
  • DB CPU represents CPU time of foreground processes
  • Total CPU Time represents foreground and background processes
  • Statistics including the word "background" measure background process time, therefore do not contribute to the DB time statistic
  • Ordered by % of DB time in descending order, followed by Statistic Name

cthz5kuhg3fz2 with last_run as ( SELECT all_runs.OWNER, all_runs.JOB_NAME, all_runs.STATUS FROM DBA_SCHEDULER_JOB_RUN_DETAILS all_runs, (SELECT OWNER, JOB_NAME, MAX(ACTUAL_START_DATE) AS START_DATE FROM DBA_SCHEDULER_JOB_RUN_DETAILS GROUP BY OWNER, JOB_NAME) latest_runs WHERE all_runs.OWNER= latest_runs.OWNER AND all_runs.JOB_NAME= latest_runs.JOB_NAME AND all_runs.ACTUAL_START_DATE=latest_runs.START_DATE ) SELECT SUM(broken), SUM(failed) FROM (SELECT DECODE(broken, :"SYS_B_00", :"SYS_B_01", :"SYS_B_02") broken, DECODE(NVL(failures, :"SYS_B_03"), :"SYS_B_04", :"SYS_B_05", :"SYS_B_06") failed FROM dba_jobs UNION ALL SELECT DECODE(STATE, :"SYS_B_07", :"SYS_B_08", :"SYS_B_09") broken, DECODE(STATUS , :"SYS_B_10", DECODE(STATE, :"SYS_B_11" , :"SYS_B_12", :"SYS_B_13", :"SYS_B_14", :"SYS_B_15"), :"SYS_B_16") failed FROM (SELECT all_jobs.OWNER, all_jobs.JOB_NAME, last_run.STATUS, all_jobs.STATE FROM last_run, DBA_SCHEDULER_JOBS all_jobs WHERE last_run.OWNER=all_jobs.OWNER AND last_run.JOB_NAME=all_jobs.JOB_NAME))

Top SQL with Top Events

  • Top SQL statements by DB Time along with the top events by DB Time for those SQLs.
  • % Activity is the percentage of DB Time due to the SQL.
  • % Event is the percentage of DB Time due to the event that the SQL is waiting on.
  • % Row Source is the percentage of DB Time due to the row source for the SQL waiting on the event.
  • Executions is the number of executions of the SQL that were sampled in ASH.

Finding 3: Commits and Rollbacks
Impact is 1.09 active sessions, 21.94% of total activity.
---------------------------------------------------------
Waits on event "log file sync" while performing COMMIT and ROLLBACK operations 
were consuming significant database time.
 
   Recommendation 1: Application Analysis
   Estimated benefit is 1.09 active sessions, 21.94% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate application logic for possible reduction in the number of 
      COMMIT operations by increasing the size of transactions.
   Rationale
      The application was performing 15698 transactions per minute with an 
      average redo size of 5371 bytes per transaction.
 
   Recommendation 2: Host Configuration
   Estimated benefit is 1.09 active sessions, 21.94% of total activity.
   --------------------------------------------------------------------
   Action
      Investigate the possibility of improving the performance of I/O to the 
      online redo log files.
   Rationale
      The average size of writes to the online redo log files was 8 K and the 
      average time per write was 1 milliseconds.
   Rationale
      The total I/O throughput on redo log files was 4.9 M per second for 
      reads and 2.9 M per second for writes.
   Rationale
      The redo log I/O throughput was divided as follows: 0% by RMAN and 
      recovery, 37% by Log Writer, 0% by Archiver, 0% by Streams AQ and 62% by 
      all other activity.
 
   Symptoms That Led to the Finding:
   ---------------------------------
      Wait class "Commit" was consuming significant database time.
      Impact is 1.09 active sessions, 21.94% of total activity.
